h3. Symptoms

* OutOfMemoryErrors
* Heap dump contains lots (> 10) IndexSearchers in the WaitableContainer
* Heap dump contains a large amount of memory allocated to FieldSortHitQueue.

h3. Cause

Plugins using their own threads to perform some form of searching either through the SearchProvider or the SearchService.

h3. Workaround

Each thread started by the plugin needs to cleanup after it has finished its processing. If its a thread pool then it should be cleaned before it executes its next task or is added back into the pool. The way to do this is to wrap your threads like:

{code}
try
{
  doWork();
}
finally
{
  JiraThreadLocalUtils.postCall(log, new JiraThreadLocalUtils.ProblemDeterminationCallback()
  {
    public void onOpenTransaction()
    {
        log.error("Thread has left transaction open.");
    }
  });
}
{code}

h3. Details

In JIRA 4.0 we keep a reference to all open Lucene IndexSearchers in the WaitableContainer. If the indexer is not closed correctly, then we end up with lots of IndexSearcher objects. They in turn hold onto the sorting arrays used by JIRA in the FieldSortHitQueue and as such chew up large amounts of memory.

Normally in JIRA we open on IndexSearcher per thread and close it in a Servlet cleanup filter. This works fine until plugins start using their own threads. If a search is performed from a non-request thread it will leave the IndexSearcher open as the cleanup filter will not run on that thread. In JIRA we make sure we close the searcher on our thread pools, however, plugins don't know to do this. 

We should fix it so that we don't need to cleanup the IndexSearchers in all these different ways. We should "open" the searcher and then immediately "close" it as you would a database or other resource. With our delayed close searcher this would cause no performance problems. 

We should also find a way to report when an IndexSearcher has not been closed as expected so that support can debug these kinds of problems easily.

